XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two-vehicle crash occurred in a four-legged, traffic signal-controlled intersection. Both roadways are straight and level. The east/west roadway has five lanes; each direction consists of two through lanes and a left turn lane. The north/south roadway has three lanes; each direction consists of one through lane and a left turn lane. The speed limit on these roadways is 56 kmph (35 mph). This crash occurred during daylight hours with no adverse atmospheric conditions.
Vehicle one (V1), a 1991 Ford Mustang, was eastbound in lane two. Vehicle two (V2), a 2001 Honda Accord, was southbound in lane one. In the intersection, the front of V1 struck the right side of V2. V1 was towed due to damage.
The driver of V1, an eighteen-year-old male, was traveling from a park to a tow yard to pick up parts for his vehicle. He was well rested and healthy, although he had just been running in the park for one-and-a-half hours (which he does three times each week), and admitted that he felt exhausted. This driver stated that he was "zoning and trying to catch my breath" just prior to the crash and did not realize that his signal was red until he was almost into the intersection. He applied the brakes and skidded into the intersection.
The driver of V2, a sixty-one-year-old male, was not interviewed. According to the police report and medical records, this driver had high cholesterol, renal failure and had a quadruple heart bypass five years previously. He takes the medications Flomax and Crestor. No further information is available for this driver.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle traveling; crossing over (passing through) intersection. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was coded to V1 as a driver related factor: inattention (i.e. daydreaming).
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded: other vehicle encroachment; from crossing street, across path. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was not coded to this vehicle.
